666. at. is often used in curses and passionate exclamations; cf. Eun. 431, Hec. 134, Pl. Most. 655, Verg. A. 2. 535. It is rarely used in blessing or entreaty; cf. Pl. Pers. 4. 3. 18, Verg. A. 8. 572.

duint, archaic for dent, as perduint for perdant; cf. Phor. 519, 976, 1005. Terence also uses duim, duit, Hee. 134, Phor. 713. Plautus employs all the following, duim, duis or duas, duit, duint.
